      <intermediateExchange id="35e4425d-3f31-53f8-8baa-28529a573eff" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" casNumber="010034-93-2" amount="1.17999617394769" intermediateExchangeId="da17f9b2-420c-5f5b-8f1c-cd5f252d64c1" activityLinkId="202c3edc-8de2-55f7-a17e-d7bc74aa40c5">
        <name xml:lang="en">hydrazine sulfate</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Calculated value based on stoichiometric calculations and literature data. 
130.12472g/mol is the molar mass of hydrazine sulfate (H6N2O4S). 
116.07952g/mol is the molar mass of azodicarbonamide (C2H4N4O2). 

Azodicarbonamide is produced from the reaction of hydrazine sulfate and urea. Sulfuric acid is used as a catalyst in the reaction. In a second step sodium hypochlorite is added to obtain the final product (Cary et al. 1999; Bakery and Rahimnejad 2013). Hydrogen sulfide is created during the reaction, it is here assumed that it is neutralized with an additional mole of sodium hypochlorite, producing additional Na and Cl. The remaining Sulphur is included in the process as by-product of inert waste.
Chemical reaction:
H6N2O4S + 2CH4N2O + 2NaOCl -&gt; C2H4N4O2 + 4H2O + 2Na + 2Cl</comment>
        <uncertainty>
          <lognormal meanValue="1.17999617394769" mu="0.16551119605510495" variance="0.0006" varianceWithPedigreeUncertainty="0.010025"/>
